Shakespeare presents fate as real and inescapable, despite Macbeth’s attempts to change it. For example,
when Macbeth orders Fleance’s murder, Fleance escapes unharmed. Macbeth is therefore unsuccessful
in his attempt to defy the prophecy that says Banquo’s descendants will be kings. Macbeth’s failure
reects a common belief in Shakespearean times about how certain people were fated to rule.
However, by the end of the play, Macbeth seems to accept that he cannot control fate. In his nal
soliloquy he describes life as “a poor player”. This metaphor shows how Macbeth thinks that people
are as powerless as actors following direction. This suggests that he no longer believes free will exists
and that his life is dictated by forces beyond his control.
In Act Five, Shakespeare shows how Macbeth’s belief in fate has become a blind belief in his invincibility.
When the enemy forces are approaching, Macbeth repeats the words of the prophecy, ”Till Birnam wood
remove to Dunsinane”, to assure himself that his defeat is impossible. This suggests that his belief in his
invincibility makes him unable to consider alternative meanings of the Witches’ ambiguous predictions.
In the extract, Shakespeare shows that Macbeth doesn’t fully trust fate to work in his favour. When the
rst apparition appears to tell Macbeth his fate, he refers to it as an “unknown power”, implying that he
believes it to have some authority. However, after the second apparition vanishes, Macbeth says he will
“take a bond of fate” and kill Macduff. This suggests that, while Macbeth believes in fate and respects its
power, he also suspects it may be unreliable, which causes him to take action to feel more secure.
Macbeth’s inconsistent attitude towards fate emphasises the difculty he has in trusting the prophecies.
On the one hand, Macbeth believes that his fate as King is determined, which is seen when he says
“Come what come may”. However, he frequently attempts to exercise his free will to full or prevent
the prophecies, such as when he has Banquo murdered. There was a widespread belief about fate
when the play was written: . Macbeth’s internal conict means that he both conforms to and
contradicts this view, so his attitude to fate would have seemed complex to an Elizabethan audience.
